events.title: Cyclists in Suits (Bike Texas)
events.description:
https://www.biketexas.org/advocacy/cyclists-in-suits-2025/

Texas’ biennial Bike Lobby Day at the Capitol is back in person for 2025! After two legislative sessions of virtual meetings, we're delighted to return to our Capitol building and meet with legislative offices in person. Mark your calendar and make plans to be in Austin on Monday, March 31 for Cyclists in Suits 2025 – Texas’ Bike Lobby Day.

In the course of one day, people who ride bikes from around the state will meet with every legislative office to tell them about our bills, what people who bike, walk, and use other active transportation in Texas need from their elected officials, and address concerns they may have. In the past, we’ve heard about bad bills and been able to take action immediately just from talking to staffers in legislative offices, and we’ve moved the needle on important legislation with an in-person visit.

To make it all happen, we need you! Register now for Cyclists in Suits and start planning your trip.

If you’re coming in from outside of Austin and would like to organize a bus or carpool from your area, let us know so we can connect you with other advocates coming from your direction.

Here’s a tentative schedule of the day:

  • 7:30am | Pre-meeting at BikeTexas – please be on time! (900 Springdale Rd., Austin, TX 78702) We’ll have coffee and bagels waiting for you.
  • 9:00am | Wheels down – we’ll bike as a group to the Capitol (other transportation arrangements will be made in the event of bad weather).
  • 9:30am – 3:00pm | Lobby teams will meet with their assigned legislative offices. We’ll visit each office at the Capitol during the course of the day.
  • 11:30am – 1:00pm | Take team lunch breaks in the Capitol cafeteria (along with lobbyists, staffers, etc.) between office visits during this time window. Please budget $15-$20 for lunch.
  • 3:00pm | Group picture on the Capitol steps.
  • 3:30pm | Ride back to BikeTexas.
  • 4:00 – 6:00pm | Share meeting notes and observations with fellow attendees and celebrate with light refreshments!

events.title: Advocate for Parking Reform at CPC
events.sourceTitle: Advocate for Parking Reform at CPC
events.description: Join us to give public comment in favor of Parking Reform in Dallas on December 5th at the City Plan Commission! Dallas could follow the lead of cities like Austin, San Jose, and Minneapolis and get rid of destructive parking mandates citywide. These mandates mean that we build too much parking, making our cities more expensive and less livable. The inefficient use of space from parking means the heat island effect is worse, makes neighborhoods accessible only by car, and drives up the cost of housing. The current proposal does other great things like limiting curb-cuts, pushing parking to the rear or side of buildings, and creating guidelines for pedestrian accessibility. To sign up to speak, you can register on the city website at this link. Sign up to speak on Item 25. You can speak either virtually or in-person. We expect for public comment to begin at about 5:30 PM, though that is just a best guess. Never given public comment before and want help? Join our Zoom Tuesday, December 3rd from 7-8 PM. Click on this Zoom link to join!

events.title: Community Bond Task Force Advocacy
events.description:
Dallas currently is crafting its 2024 bond. Historically, housing has received little funding by the city. But this bond is an opportunity to change that. We are going to be at the 6:30 PM August 15th Community Bond Task Force Meeting in conjunction with the Dallas Housing Coalition to advocate for $200 million for affordable housing in the bond. We want this to be an overwhelming show of support, and we hope to see you on the 15th! Click the link to sign up to speak either virtually or in-person.August is Membership Month at YIMBYAction, our parent organization. Speaking on the 15th gets you free membership for a year with YIMBYAction along with a free T-Shirt. If you can't speak on the 15th, you can also speak at the Community Bond Task Force meeting on the 22nd, but our main group will be going on the 15th. RSVPing helps us keep track of who speaks and receives the YIMBYAction membership. If you've never spoken before at a public meeting, this is a perfect one to advocate for housing! There will be lots of fellow pro-housing speakers there, and it's in the evening too. We recommend making your speech about the need for affordable housing as personal as possible, but below are some general ideas and stats (many courtesy of Dallas Housing Coalition) that you can use. Note, you can either prepare something to say or speak extemporaneously.- Dallas needs 100,000 new or refurbished affordable homes by 2033 to meet our housing demand.- San Antonio ($150 million) and Austin ($350 million) both passed by a large majority significant affordable housing bonds in 2022.- Dallas lost 38,000 homes valued around $100,000, the kind of home most affordable for first time homebuyers, in the past five years.- Studies have shown that new affordable housing in a neighborhood is correlated with a decrease in crime in the area. - $200 million could fund the creation of thousands of affordable units.- Higher cost of housing is tied to increased homelessness, heightening the need for funding to help fight homelessness.- Since 2010, Dallas has delivered only 1.9 new, deed-restricted affordable
units per 1,000 residents, ranking 21st of 32 big cities in the affordable unit production.- Dallas ranks 10th out of the 12 largest cities for affordable housing units in “high opportunity” census tracts and remains the
most segregated big city in Texas – and among the most segregated big cities in the nation.
 - Lack of housing affordability forces families to make tradeoffs with basic daily needs (e.g. food, clothing, transportation). On
average, families at or below 50% AMI are spending nearly half their income on housing each month.

events.title: Advocate for Transit-Oriented Development on August 3rd... Get a Free T-Shirt!
events.sourceTitle: Advocate for Transit-Oriented Development on August 3rd... Get a Free T-Shirt!
events.description: August is Membership Month at YIMBYAction, our parent organization. To get free membership for a year with YIMBYAction and receive a free T-Shirt, there are THREE opportunities to advocate for housing. You only need to speak at one of the three for the T-Shirt and membership. Note, you can speak either virtually or in-person. The other two opportunities will be the Community Bond Task Force Meetings on August 15th and 22nd at 6:30 PM. Stay tuned for more info on those dates. The first opportunity is this Thursday!Thursday August 3rd CPC Meeting at 12:30 PM in Support of Walnut Hill Rezoning: Link to sign up to Speak for Item 8: 23-2037 - Z212-307(RM).This case got delayed from the July 20th meeting City Plan Commission (CPC) meeting. The rezoning is to allow TOD (Transit-Oriented Development) on what is currently a shopping center at The Hill, close to the Walnut Hill DART station. If approved, the rezoning would allow for up to 1,700 homes, of which more than 150 would be affordable. Read more about the case.The CPC meeting starts at 12:30. Since the rezoning is for Item 8, it could be heard around 1 PM but it is impossible to say for sure. Unless you are free for all of Thursday afternoon, we recommend speaking virtually because of the time uncertainty. You will be able to join the meeting virtually here. NOTE: If you can't speak Thursday, you can submit a public comment in support here. You can select every Commissioner, and again it is Item 8: 23-2037 - Z212-307(RM). Feel free to use the language below when submitting your comment or for preparing to speak."Hello, I'm here to speak in favor of this rezoning. I'm excited to see this proposal to build a mixed-use community in what is currently simply a commercial area. It's even better that this rezoning is close to the Walnut Hill DART station. This kind of Transit-Oriented Development is something that we don't have enough of here in Dallas, but it's exactly what we need in order to be a better city. Building up to 1,700 homes where there are currently none will help make Dallas more affordable for all, help environmentally by increasing public transit ridership and reducing sprawl, decrease displacement of existing residents, and create increased tax revenue to provide for better public services in Dallas. I hope that you not only approve the rezoning today but also look at how the city can proactively rezone other areas around DART stations to spur this kind of development."

events.title: Paved Paradise - Dallas Parking Reform
events.description: DATE CHANGE: The new event date is December 17th. Join us and hear from Henry Grabar, author of the award-winning book, Paved Paradise: How Parking Explains the World. Parking policies guide much of the form and design of our cities. They entrap cities in a cycle of car-dependency that has negative impacts on housing costs, carbon emissions, air quality, and city budget. Important conversations are happening in Dallas around parking reform, with City Council expected to vote on a new parking policy in early 2025.This evening will be a great primer on the real life impacts of parking policies. So whether you've never parked a car in your life or if you've read the Dallas City parking requirements front to back, this is a great opportunity for anyone to learn more about a subject that is critical to the future of our city.RSVP to receive the Zoom link for the event.

events.title: Speak Up for Housing on December 6th!
events.sourceTitle: Speak Up for Housing on December 6th!
events.description: We need to speak up for housing on December 6th at 9 AM at City Council! There are two huge housing issues that council will be hearing about, and we need to PACK the room with housing advocates. To sign up to speak, go to https://dallascityhall.com/government/citysecretary/pages/ccrules.aspx or call 214-670-3738 to sign up. You can speak virtually or in-person, but we recommend speaking in-person if possible. Haven't spoken before at council and want advice on what to say? RSVP and join us for a Zoom on November 29th at 7:00 PM. The first and most pressing issue on December 6th is the 2024 Bond. We, as part of the broader Dallas Housing Coalition, have been asking for $200 million for affordable housing in the bond. The Community Bond Task Force has slashed that amount to less than $50 million. That is unacceptable in a housing crisis. December 6th will have Council hear proposals from the City Manager and the Bond Task Force on the bond for the first time. The good news is that members of city council have indicated already that they want more money for housing. Now, we have to make them follow through on that and make sure they hear us loud and clear on the 6th.The other issue is Minimum Lot Size reform and legalizing missing middle housing. Council is having an initial hearing from staff about what these reforms could do. It's an important step in these reforms coming to council for a vote, hopefully in the near future. Note, that something like minimum lot size reform would make the housing bond more effective by making any housing built be more efficient. December 6th is the kind of day why Dallas Neighbors for Housing exists. We know that speaking at City Council on a weekday morning favors those capable of making the time instead of working, but we have to play the game. Speaking, or at least showing up to support, does make a big difference. You also can send an email to City Council here: https://actionnetwork.org/letters/dallas-city-council-prioritize-affordable-housing.

events.title: May 9th: Let's Show Out Again for Forward Dallas!
events.sourceTitle: May 9th: Let's Show Out Again for Forward Dallas!
events.description:
At the first citywide Forward Dallas meeting, pro-housing advocates outnumbered those trying to keep the status quo (https://candysdirt.com/2024/04/22/activists-come-out-swinging-on-both-sides-of-forwarddallas-comprehensive-land-use-plan/). But we can expect for lots more people to show up on May 9th. So join us once again at City Hall again on May 9th from 6-9 PM.This is the rare chance where public comment is being taken in the evening, instead of during the weekday. For this meeting, no online registration is required if you are speaking in person. If you can't make it in person and plan on speaking virtually, you can register here starting on Friday, May 3rd. If you've never given a public comment before, don't be intimidated! Showing up and telling your truth around housing is what matters the most. Specifically, we are fighting for a Forward Dallas that advocates for 1. A Community Residential Placetype that accommodates more housing within single-family neighborhoods.2. An emphasis on Mixed-Use and more housing in commercial and formerly industrial areas. 3. ADUs by right across Dallas neighborhoods.Read more about Forward Dallas here: https://www.dallasneighborsforhousing.org/forward-dallas.
